<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-334-155  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 334 155.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Feb 13 1989 v6 n6 p13(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Satellites won't fade away, report finds.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taff, Anita.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A study by Communications Satellite Corp states that users willcontinue to rely on both satellites and fiber-optic cables forinternational telecommunications into the next century.andP;  The studywas commissioned by COMSAT, the US representative in theInternational Telecommunications Satellite Organization, to studythe future of satellite technology.andP;  Many analysts fear thattransoceanic fiber cables will render the usefulness of satellitesfor international telecommunication purposes obsolete.andP;  The studyexplores the expected role of satellites during the years 1995 to2005.andP;  The study concludes that satellite-based and fiber-basedservices will be priced competitively in the future, and thatservices using some types of satellites will be as much as 45percent less expensive than international services over fiber.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Communications Satellite Corp. (reports).andO;Ticker:    CQ.andO;Topic:     StudySatellitesFiber OpticsInternationalTelecommunicationsConferencesInternational Telecommunications Satellite Organization.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>